#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:5
msgid "Structured arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:8
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:10
msgid ""
"Structured arrays are ndarrays whose datatype is a composition of simpler "
"datatypes organized as a sequence of named :term:`fields <field>`. For "
"example, ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:14
msgid ""
">>> x = np.array([('Rex', 9, 81.0), ('Fido', 3, 27.0)],\n"
"...              dtype=[('name', 'U10'), ('age', 'i4'), ('weight', 'f4')])\n"
">>> x\n"
"array([('Rex', 9, 81.), ('Fido', 3, 27.)],\n"
"      dtype=[('name', '<U10'), ('age', '<i4'), ('weight', '<f4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:20
msgid ""
"Here ``x`` is a one-dimensional array of length two whose datatype is a "
"structure with three fields: 1. A string of length 10 or less named 'name', "
"2. a 32-bit integer named 'age', and 3. a 32-bit float named 'weight'."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:24
msgid "If you index ``x`` at position 1 you get a structure::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:26
msgid ""
">>> x[1]\n"
"np.void(('Fido', 3, 27.0), dtype=[('name', '<U10'), ('age', '<i4'), "
"('weight', '<f4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:29
msgid ""
"You can access and modify individual fields of a structured array by "
"indexing with the field name::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:32
msgid ""
">>> x['age']\n"
"array([9, 3], dtype=int32)\n"
">>> x['age'] = 5\n"
">>> x\n"
"array([('Rex', 5, 81.), ('Fido', 5, 27.)],\n"
"      dtype=[('name', '<U10'), ('age', '<i4'), ('weight', '<f4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:39
msgid ""
"Structured datatypes are designed to be able to mimic 'structs' in the C "
"language, and share a similar memory layout. They are meant for interfacing "
"with C code and for low-level manipulation of structured buffers, for "
"example for interpreting binary blobs. For these purposes they support "
"specialized features such as subarrays, nested datatypes, and unions, and "
"allow control over the memory layout of the structure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:46
msgid ""
"Users looking to manipulate tabular data, such as stored in csv files, may "
"find other pydata projects more suitable, such as xarray, pandas, or "
"DataArray. These provide a high-level interface for tabular data analysis "
"and are better optimized for that use. For instance, the C-struct-like "
"memory layout of structured arrays in numpy can lead to poor cache behavior "
"in comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:55
msgid "Structured datatypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:57
msgid ""
"A structured datatype can be thought of as a sequence of bytes of a certain "
"length (the structure's :term:`itemsize`) which is interpreted as a "
"collection of fields. Each field has a name, a datatype, and a byte offset "
"within the structure. The datatype of a field may be any numpy datatype "
"including other structured datatypes, and it may also be a :term:`subarray "
"data type` which behaves like an ndarray of a specified shape. The offsets "
"of the fields are arbitrary, and fields may even overlap. These offsets are "
"usually determined automatically by numpy, but can also be specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:67
msgid "Structured datatype creation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:69
msgid ""
"Structured datatypes may be created using the function :func:`numpy.dtype`. "
"There are 4 alternative forms of specification which vary in flexibility and "
"conciseness. These are further documented in the :ref:`Data Type Objects "
"<arrays.dtypes.constructing>` reference page, and in summary they are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:75
msgid "A list of tuples, one tuple per field"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:77
msgid ""
"Each tuple has the form ``(fieldname, datatype, shape)`` where shape is "
"optional. ``fieldname`` is a string (or tuple if titles are used, see :ref:"
"`Field Titles <titles>` below), ``datatype`` may be any object convertible "
"to a datatype, and ``shape`` is a tuple of integers specifying subarray "
"shape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:86
msgid ""
"If ``fieldname`` is the empty string ``''``, the field will be given a "
"default name of the form ``f#``, where ``#`` is the integer index of the "
"field, counting from 0 from the left::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:90
msgid ""
">>> np.dtype([('x', 'f4'), ('', 'i4'), ('z', 'i8')])\n"
"dtype([('x', '<f4'), ('f1', '<i4'), ('z', '<i8')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:93
msgid ""
"The byte offsets of the fields within the structure and the total structure "
"itemsize are determined automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:96
msgid "A string of comma-separated dtype specifications"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:98
msgid ""
"In this shorthand notation any of the :ref:`string dtype specifications "
"<arrays.dtypes.constructing>` may be used in a string and separated by "
"commas. The itemsize and byte offsets of the fields are determined "
"automatically, and the field names are given the default names ``f0``, "
"``f1``, etc. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:104
msgid ""
">>> np.dtype('i8, f4, S3')\n"
"dtype([('f0', '<i8'), ('f1', '<f4'), ('f2', 'S3')])\n"
">>> np.dtype('3int8, float32, (2, 3)float64')\n"
"dtype([('f0', 'i1', (3,)), ('f1', '<f4'), ('f2', '<f8', (2, 3))])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:109
msgid "A dictionary of field parameter arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:111
msgid ""
"This is the most flexible form of specification since it allows control over "
"the byte-offsets of the fields and the itemsize of the structure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:114
msgid ""
"The dictionary has two required keys, 'names' and 'formats', and four "
"optional keys, 'offsets', 'itemsize', 'aligned' and 'titles'. The values for "
"'names' and 'formats' should respectively be a list of field names and a "
"list of dtype specifications, of the same length. The optional 'offsets' "
"value should be a list of integer byte-offsets, one for each field within "
"the structure. If 'offsets' is not given the offsets are determined "
"automatically. The optional 'itemsize' value should be an integer describing "
"the total size in bytes of the dtype, which must be large enough to contain "
"all the fields. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:125
msgid ""
">>> np.dtype({'names': ['col1', 'col2'], 'formats': ['i4', 'f4']})\n"
"dtype([('col1', '<i4'), ('col2', '<f4')])\n"
">>> np.dtype({'names': ['col1', 'col2'],\n"
"...           'formats': ['i4', 'f4'],\n"
"...           'offsets': [0, 4],\n"
"...           'itemsize': 12})\n"
"dtype({'names': ['col1', 'col2'], 'formats': ['<i4', '<f4'], 'offsets': [0, "
"4], 'itemsize': 12})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:133
msgid ""
"Offsets may be chosen such that the fields overlap, though this will mean "
"that assigning to one field may clobber any overlapping field's data. As an "
"exception, fields of :class:`numpy.object_` type cannot overlap with other "
"fields, because of the risk of clobbering the internal object pointer and "
"then dereferencing it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:139
msgid ""
"The optional 'aligned' value can be set to ``True`` to make the automatic "
"offset computation use aligned offsets (see :ref:`offsets-and-alignment`), "
"as if the 'align' keyword argument of :func:`numpy.dtype` had been set to "
"True."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:144
msgid ""
"The optional 'titles' value should be a list of titles of the same length as "
"'names', see :ref:`Field Titles <titles>` below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:147
msgid "A dictionary of field names"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:149
msgid ""
"The keys of the dictionary are the field names and the values are tuples "
"specifying type and offset::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:152
msgid ""
">>> np.dtype({'col1': ('i1', 0), 'col2': ('f4', 1)})\n"
"dtype([('col1', 'i1'), ('col2', '<f4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:155
msgid ""
"This form was discouraged because Python dictionaries did not preserve order "
"in Python versions before Python 3.6. :ref:`Field Titles <titles>` may be "
"specified by using a 3-tuple, see below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:160
msgid "Manipulating and displaying structured datatypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:162
msgid ""
"The list of field names of a structured datatype can be found in the "
"``names`` attribute of the dtype object::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:165
msgid ""
">>> d = np.dtype([('x', 'i8'), ('y', 'f4')])\n"
">>> d.names\n"
"('x', 'y')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:169
msgid "The dtype of each individual field can be looked up by name::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:171
msgid ""
">>> d['x']\n"
"dtype('int64')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:174
msgid ""
"The field names may be modified by assigning to the ``names`` attribute "
"using a sequence of strings of the same length."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:177
msgid ""
"The dtype object also has a dictionary-like attribute, ``fields``, whose "
"keys are the field names (and :ref:`Field Titles <titles>`, see below) and "
"whose values are tuples containing the dtype and byte offset of each "
"field. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:181
msgid ""
">>> d.fields\n"
"mappingproxy({'x': (dtype('int64'), 0), 'y': (dtype('float32'), 8)})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:184
msgid ""
"Both the ``names`` and ``fields`` attributes will equal ``None`` for "
"unstructured arrays. The recommended way to test if a dtype is structured is "
"with `if dt.names is not None` rather than `if dt.names`, to account for "
"dtypes with 0 fields."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:189
msgid ""
"The string representation of a structured datatype is shown in the \"list of "
"tuples\" form if possible, otherwise numpy falls back to using the more "
"general dictionary form."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:196
msgid "Automatic byte offsets and alignment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:198
msgid ""
"Numpy uses one of two methods to automatically determine the field byte "
"offsets and the overall itemsize of a structured datatype, depending on "
"whether ``align=True`` was specified as a keyword argument to :func:`numpy."
"dtype`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:202
msgid ""
"By default (``align=False``), numpy will pack the fields together such that "
"each field starts at the byte offset the previous field ended, and the "
"fields are contiguous in memory. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:206
msgid ""
">>> def print_offsets(d):\n"
"...     print(\"offsets:\", [d.fields[name][1] for name in d.names])\n"
"...     print(\"itemsize:\", d.itemsize)\n"
">>> print_offsets(np.dtype('u1, u1, i4, u1, i8, u2'))\n"
"offsets: [0, 1, 2, 6, 7, 15]\n"
"itemsize: 17"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:213
msgid ""
"If ``align=True`` is set, numpy will pad the structure in the same way many "
"C compilers would pad a C-struct. Aligned structures can give a performance "
"improvement in some cases, at the cost of increased datatype size. Padding "
"bytes are inserted between fields such that each field's byte offset will be "
"a multiple of that field's alignment, which is usually equal to the field's "
"size in bytes for simple datatypes, see :c:member:`PyArray_Descr."
"alignment`.  The structure will also have trailing padding added so that its "
"itemsize is a multiple of the largest field's alignment. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:222
msgid ""
">>> print_offsets(np.dtype('u1, u1, i4, u1, i8, u2', align=True))\n"
"offsets: [0, 1, 4, 8, 16, 24]\n"
"itemsize: 32"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:226
msgid ""
"Note that although almost all modern C compilers pad in this way by default, "
"padding in C structs is C-implementation-dependent so this memory layout is "
"not guaranteed to exactly match that of a corresponding struct in a C "
"program. Some work may be needed, either on the numpy side or the C side, to "
"obtain exact correspondence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:232
msgid ""
"If offsets were specified using the optional ``offsets`` key in the "
"dictionary-based dtype specification, setting ``align=True`` will check that "
"each field's offset is a multiple of its size and that the itemsize is a "
"multiple of the largest field size, and raise an exception if not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:237
msgid ""
"If the offsets of the fields and itemsize of a structured array satisfy the "
"alignment conditions, the array will have the ``ALIGNED`` :attr:`flag <numpy."
"ndarray.flags>` set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:241
msgid ""
"A convenience function :func:`numpy.lib.recfunctions.repack_fields` converts "
"an aligned dtype or array to a packed one and vice versa. It takes either a "
"dtype or structured ndarray as an argument, and returns a copy with fields "
"re-packed, with or without padding bytes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:249
msgid "Field titles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:251
msgid ""
"In addition to field names, fields may also have an associated :term:"
"`title`, an alternate name, which is sometimes used as an additional "
"description or alias for the field. The title may be used to index an array, "
"just like a field name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:256
msgid ""
"To add titles when using the list-of-tuples form of dtype specification, the "
"field name may be specified as a tuple of two strings instead of a single "
"string, which will be the field's title and field name respectively. For "
"example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:261
msgid ""
">>> np.dtype([(('my title', 'name'), 'f4')])\n"
"dtype([(('my title', 'name'), '<f4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:264
msgid ""
"When using the first form of dictionary-based specification, the titles may "
"be supplied as an extra ``'titles'`` key as described above. When using the "
"second (discouraged) dictionary-based specification, the title can be "
"supplied by providing a 3-element tuple ``(datatype, offset, title)`` "
"instead of the usual 2-element tuple::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:270
msgid ""
">>> np.dtype({'name': ('i4', 0, 'my title')})\n"
"dtype([(('my title', 'name'), '<i4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:273
msgid ""
"The ``dtype.fields`` dictionary will contain titles as keys, if any titles "
"are used.  This means effectively that a field with a title will be "
"represented twice in the fields dictionary. The tuple values for these "
"fields will also have a third element, the field title. Because of this, and "
"because the ``names`` attribute preserves the field order while the "
"``fields`` attribute may not, it is recommended to iterate through the "
"fields of a dtype using the ``names`` attribute of the dtype, which will not "
"list titles, as in::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:282
msgid ""
">>> for name in d.names:\n"
"...     print(d.fields[name][:2])\n"
"(dtype('int64'), 0)\n"
"(dtype('float32'), 8)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:288
msgid "Union types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:290
msgid ""
"Structured datatypes are implemented in numpy to have base type :class:"
"`numpy.void` by default, but it is possible to interpret other numpy types "
"as structured types using the ``(base_dtype, dtype)`` form of dtype "
"specification described in :ref:`Data Type Objects <arrays.dtypes."
"constructing>`.  Here, ``base_dtype`` is the desired underlying dtype, and "
"fields and flags will be copied from ``dtype``. This dtype is similar to a "
"'union' in C."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:299
msgid "Indexing and assignment to structured arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:302
msgid "Assigning data to a structured array"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:304
msgid ""
"There are a number of ways to assign values to a structured array: Using "
"python tuples, using scalar values, or using other structured arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:308
msgid "Assignment from Python Native Types (Tuples)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:310
msgid ""
"The simplest way to assign values to a structured array is using python "
"tuples. Each assigned value should be a tuple of length equal to the number "
"of fields in the array, and not a list or array as these will trigger "
"numpy's broadcasting rules. The tuple's elements are assigned to the "
"successive fields of the array, from left to right::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:316
msgid ""
">>> x = np.array([(1, 2, 3), (4, 5, 6)], dtype='i8, f4, f8')\n"
">>> x[1] = (7, 8, 9)\n"
">>> x\n"
"array([(1, 2., 3.), (7, 8., 9.)],\n"
"     dtype=[('f0', '<i8'), ('f1', '<f4'), ('f2', '<f8')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:323
msgid "Assignment from Scalars"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:325
msgid ""
"A scalar assigned to a structured element will be assigned to all fields. "
"This happens when a scalar is assigned to a structured array, or when an "
"unstructured array is assigned to a structured array::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:329
msgid ""
">>> x = np.zeros(2, dtype='i8, f4, ?, S1')\n"
">>> x[:] = 3\n"
">>> x\n"
"array([(3, 3., True, b'3'), (3, 3., True, b'3')],\n"
"      dtype=[('f0', '<i8'), ('f1', '<f4'), ('f2', '?'), ('f3', 'S1')])\n"
">>> x[:] = np.arange(2)\n"
">>> x\n"
"array([(0, 0., False, b'0'), (1, 1., True, b'1')],\n"
"      dtype=[('f0', '<i8'), ('f1', '<f4'), ('f2', '?'), ('f3', 'S1')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:339
msgid ""
"Structured arrays can also be assigned to unstructured arrays, but only if "
"the structured datatype has just a single field::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:342
msgid ""
">>> twofield = np.zeros(2, dtype=[('A', 'i4'), ('B', 'i4')])\n"
">>> onefield = np.zeros(2, dtype=[('A', 'i4')])\n"
">>> nostruct = np.zeros(2, dtype='i4')\n"
">>> nostruct[:] = twofield\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"...\n"
"TypeError: Cannot cast array data from dtype([('A', '<i4'), ('B', '<i4')]) "
"to dtype('int32') according to the rule 'unsafe'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:351
msgid "Assignment from other Structured Arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:353
msgid ""
"Assignment between two structured arrays occurs as if the source elements "
"had been converted to tuples and then assigned to the destination elements. "
"That is, the first field of the source array is assigned to the first field "
"of the destination array, and the second field likewise, and so on, "
"regardless of field names. Structured arrays with a different number of "
"fields cannot be assigned to each other. Bytes of the destination structure "
"which are not included in any of the fields are unaffected. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:361
msgid ""
">>> a = np.zeros(3, dtype=[('a', 'i8'), ('b', 'f4'), ('c', 'S3')])\n"
">>> b = np.ones(3, dtype=[('x', 'f4'), ('y', 'S3'), ('z', 'O')])\n"
">>> b[:] = a\n"
">>> b\n"
"array([(0., b'0.0', b''), (0., b'0.0', b''), (0., b'0.0', b'')],\n"
"      dtype=[('x', '<f4'), ('y', 'S3'), ('z', 'O')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:370
msgid "Assignment involving subarrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:372
msgid ""
"When assigning to fields which are subarrays, the assigned value will first "
"be broadcast to the shape of the subarray."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:376
msgid "Indexing structured arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:379
msgid "Accessing Individual Fields"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:381
msgid ""
"Individual fields of a structured array may be accessed and modified by "
"indexing the array with the field name. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:384
msgid ""
">>> x = np.array([(1, 2), (3, 4)], dtype=[('foo', 'i8'), ('bar', 'f4')])\n"
">>> x['foo']\n"
"array([1, 3])\n"
">>> x['foo'] = 10\n"
">>> x\n"
"array([(10, 2.), (10, 4.)],\n"
"      dtype=[('foo', '<i8'), ('bar', '<f4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:392
msgid ""
"The resulting array is a view into the original array. It shares the same "
"memory locations and writing to the view will modify the original array. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:395
msgid ""
">>> y = x['bar']\n"
">>> y[:] = 11\n"
">>> x\n"
"array([(10, 11.), (10, 11.)],\n"
"      dtype=[('foo', '<i8'), ('bar', '<f4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:401
msgid ""
"This view has the same dtype and itemsize as the indexed field, so it is "
"typically a non-structured array, except in the case of nested structures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:407
msgid ""
"If the accessed field is a subarray, the dimensions of the subarray are "
"appended to the shape of the result::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:410
msgid ""
">>> x = np.zeros((2, 2), dtype=[('a', np.int32), ('b', np.float64, (3, "
"3))])\n"
">>> x['a'].shape\n"
"(2, 2)\n"
">>> x['b'].shape\n"
"(2, 2, 3, 3)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:417
msgid "Accessing Multiple Fields"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:419
msgid ""
"One can index and assign to a structured array with a multi-field index, "
"where the index is a list of field names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:423
msgid ""
"The behavior of multi-field indexes changed from Numpy 1.15 to Numpy 1.16."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:425
msgid ""
"The result of indexing with a multi-field index is a view into the original "
"array, as follows::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:428
msgid ""
">>> a = np.zeros(3, dtype=[('a', 'i4'), ('b', 'i4'), ('c', 'f4')])\n"
">>> a[['a', 'c']]\n"
"array([(0, 0.), (0, 0.), (0, 0.)],\n"
"     dtype={'names': ['a', 'c'], 'formats': ['<i4', '<f4'], 'offsets': [0, "
"8], 'itemsize': 12})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:433
msgid ""
"Assignment to the view modifies the original array. The view's fields will "
"be in the order they were indexed. Note that unlike for single-field "
"indexing, the dtype of the view has the same itemsize as the original array, "
"and has fields at the same offsets as in the original array, and unindexed "
"fields are merely missing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:440
msgid ""
"In Numpy 1.15, indexing an array with a multi-field index returned a copy of "
"the result above, but with fields packed together in memory as if passed "
"through :func:`numpy.lib.recfunctions.repack_fields`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:444
msgid ""
"The new behavior as of Numpy 1.16 leads to extra \"padding\" bytes at the "
"location of unindexed fields compared to 1.15. You will need to update any "
"code which depends on the data having a \"packed\" layout. For instance code "
"such as::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:449
msgid ""
">>> a[['a', 'c']].view('i8')  # Fails in Numpy 1.16\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"   File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n"
"ValueError: When changing to a smaller dtype, its size must be a divisor of "
"the size of original dtype"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:454
msgid ""
"will need to be changed. This code has raised a ``FutureWarning`` since "
"Numpy 1.12, and similar code has raised ``FutureWarning`` since 1.7."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:457
msgid ""
"In 1.16 a number of functions have been introduced in the :mod:`numpy.lib."
"recfunctions` module to help users account for this change. These are :func:"
"`numpy.lib.recfunctions.repack_fields`. :func:`numpy.lib.recfunctions."
"structured_to_unstructured`, :func:`numpy.lib.recfunctions."
"unstructured_to_structured`, :func:`numpy.lib.recfunctions."
"apply_along_fields`, :func:`numpy.lib.recfunctions.assign_fields_by_name`,  "
"and :func:`numpy.lib.recfunctions.require_fields`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:467
msgid ""
"The function :func:`numpy.lib.recfunctions.repack_fields` can always be used "
"to reproduce the old behavior, as it will return a packed copy of the "
"structured array. The code above, for example, can be replaced with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:475
msgid ""
"Furthermore, numpy now provides a new function :func:`numpy.lib.recfunctions."
"structured_to_unstructured` which is a safer and more efficient alternative "
"for users who wish to convert structured arrays to unstructured arrays, as "
"the view above is often intended to do. This function allows safe conversion "
"to an unstructured type taking into account padding, often avoids a copy, "
"and also casts the datatypes as needed, unlike the view. Code such as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:487
msgid "can be made safer by replacing with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:496
msgid ""
"Assignment to an array with a multi-field index modifies the original array::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:498
msgid ""
">>> a[['a', 'c']] = (2, 3)\n"
">>> a\n"
"array([(2, 0, 3.), (2, 0, 3.), (2, 0, 3.)],\n"
"      dtype=[('a', '<i4'), ('b', '<i4'), ('c', '<f4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:503
msgid ""
"This obeys the structured array assignment rules described above. For "
"example, this means that one can swap the values of two fields using "
"appropriate multi-field indexes::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:507
msgid ">>> a[['a', 'c']] = a[['c', 'a']]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:510
msgid "Indexing with an Integer to get a Structured Scalar"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:512
msgid ""
"Indexing a single element of a structured array (with an integer index) "
"returns a structured scalar::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:515
msgid ""
">>> x = np.array([(1, 2., 3.)], dtype='i, f, f')\n"
">>> scalar = x[0]\n"
">>> scalar\n"
"np.void((1, 2.0, 3.0), dtype=[('f0', '<i4'), ('f1', '<f4'), ('f2', '<f4')])\n"
">>> type(scalar)\n"
"<class 'numpy.void'>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:522
msgid ""
"Unlike other numpy scalars, structured scalars are mutable and act like "
"views into the original array, such that modifying the scalar will modify "
"the original array. Structured scalars also support access and assignment by "
"field name::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:527
msgid ""
">>> x = np.array([(1, 2), (3, 4)], dtype=[('foo', 'i8'), ('bar', 'f4')])\n"
">>> s = x[0]\n"
">>> s['bar'] = 100\n"
">>> x\n"
"array([(1, 100.), (3, 4.)],\n"
"      dtype=[('foo', '<i8'), ('bar', '<f4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:534
msgid ""
"Similarly to tuples, structured scalars can also be indexed with an integer::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:536
msgid ""
">>> scalar = np.array([(1, 2., 3.)], dtype='i, f, f')[0]\n"
">>> scalar[0]\n"
"np.int32(1)\n"
">>> scalar[1] = 4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:541
msgid ""
"Thus, tuples might be thought of as the native Python equivalent to numpy's "
"structured types, much like native python integers are the equivalent to "
"numpy's integer types. Structured scalars may be converted to a tuple by "
"calling `numpy.ndarray.item`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:546
msgid ""
">>> scalar.item(), type(scalar.item())\n"
"((1, 4.0, 3.0), <class 'tuple'>)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:550
msgid "Viewing structured arrays containing objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:552
msgid ""
"In order to prevent clobbering object pointers in fields of :class:`object` "
"type, numpy currently does not allow views of structured arrays containing "
"objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:559
msgid "Structure comparison and promotion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:561
msgid ""
"If the dtypes of two void structured arrays are equal, testing the equality "
"of the arrays will result in a boolean array with the dimensions of the "
"original arrays, with elements set to ``True`` where all fields of the "
"corresponding structures are equal::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:566
msgid ""
">>> a = np.array([(1, 1), (2, 2)], dtype=[('a', 'i4'), ('b', 'i4')])\n"
">>> b = np.array([(1, 1), (2, 3)], dtype=[('a', 'i4'), ('b', 'i4')])\n"
">>> a == b\n"
"array([True, False])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:571
msgid ""
"NumPy will promote individual field datatypes to perform the comparison. So "
"the following is also valid (note the ``'f4'`` dtype for the ``'a'`` field):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:578
msgid ""
"To compare two structured arrays, it must be possible to promote them to a "
"common dtype as returned by `numpy.result_type` and `numpy.promote_types`. "
"This enforces that the number of fields, the field names, and the field "
"titles must match precisely. When promotion is not possible, for example due "
"to mismatching field names, NumPy will raise an error. Promotion between two "
"structured dtypes results in a canonical dtype that ensures native byte-"
"order for all fields::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:587
msgid ""
">>> np.result_type(np.dtype(\"i,>i\"))\n"
"dtype([('f0', '<i4'), ('f1', '<i4')])\n"
">>> np.result_type(np.dtype(\"i,>i\"), np.dtype(\"i,i\"))\n"
"dtype([('f0', '<i4'), ('f1', '<i4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:592
msgid ""
"The resulting dtype from promotion is also guaranteed to be packed, meaning "
"that all fields are ordered contiguously and any unnecessary padding is "
"removed::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:596
msgid ""
">>> dt = np.dtype(\"i1,V3,i4,V1\")[[\"f0\", \"f2\"]]\n"
">>> dt\n"
"dtype({'names': ['f0', 'f2'], 'formats': ['i1', '<i4'], 'offsets': [0, 4], "
"'itemsize': 9})\n"
">>> np.result_type(dt)\n"
"dtype([('f0', 'i1'), ('f2', '<i4')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:602
msgid ""
"Note that the result prints without ``offsets`` or ``itemsize`` indicating "
"no additional padding. If a structured dtype is created with ``align=True`` "
"ensuring that ``dtype.isalignedstruct`` is true, this property is preserved::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:607
msgid ""
">>> dt = np.dtype(\"i1,V3,i4,V1\", align=True)[[\"f0\", \"f2\"]]\n"
">>> dt\n"
"dtype({'names': ['f0', 'f2'], 'formats': ['i1', '<i4'], 'offsets': [0, 4], "
"'itemsize': 12}, align=True)\n"
"\n"
">>> np.result_type(dt)\n"
"dtype([('f0', 'i1'), ('f2', '<i4')], align=True)\n"
">>> np.result_type(dt).isalignedstruct\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:616
msgid ""
"When promoting multiple dtypes, the result is aligned if any of the inputs "
"is::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:618
msgid ""
">>> np.result_type(np.dtype(\"i,i\"), np.dtype(\"i,i\", align=True))\n"
"dtype([('f0', '<i4'), ('f1', '<i4')], align=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:621
msgid ""
"The ``<`` and ``>`` operators always return ``False`` when comparing void "
"structured arrays, and arithmetic and bitwise operations are not supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:624
msgid ""
"Before NumPy 1.23, a warning was given and ``False`` returned when promotion "
"to a common dtype failed. Further, promotion was much more restrictive: It "
"would reject the mixed float/integer comparison example above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:631
msgid "Record arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:633
msgid ""
"As an optional convenience numpy provides an ndarray subclass, :class:`numpy."
"recarray` that allows access to fields of structured arrays by attribute "
"instead of only by index. Record arrays use a special datatype, :class:"
"`numpy.record`, that allows field access by attribute on the structured "
"scalars obtained from the array. The ``numpy.rec`` module provides functions "
"for creating recarrays from various objects. Additional helper functions for "
"creating and manipulating structured arrays can be found in :mod:`numpy.lib."
"recfunctions`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:643
msgid ""
"The simplest way to create a record array is with :func:`numpy.rec.array "
"<numpy.rec.array>`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:646
msgid ""
">>> recordarr = np.rec.array([(1, 2., 'Hello'), (2, 3., \"World\")],\n"
"...                    dtype=[('foo', 'i4'),('bar', 'f4'), ('baz', 'S10')])\n"
">>> recordarr.bar\n"
"array([2., 3.], dtype=float32)\n"
">>> recordarr[1:2]\n"
"rec.array([(2, 3., b'World')],\n"
"      dtype=[('foo', '<i4'), ('bar', '<f4'), ('baz', 'S10')])\n"
">>> recordarr[1:2].foo\n"
"array([2], dtype=int32)\n"
">>> recordarr.foo[1:2]\n"
"array([2], dtype=int32)\n"
">>> recordarr[1].baz\n"
"b'World'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:660
msgid ""
":func:`numpy.rec.array <numpy.rec.array>` can convert a wide variety of "
"arguments into record arrays, including structured arrays::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:663
msgid ""
">>> arr = np.array([(1, 2., 'Hello'), (2, 3., \"World\")],\n"
"...             dtype=[('foo', 'i4'), ('bar', 'f4'), ('baz', 'S10')])\n"
">>> recordarr = np.rec.array(arr)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:667
msgid ""
"The ``numpy.rec`` module provides a number of other convenience functions "
"for creating record arrays, see :ref:`record array creation routines "
"<routines.array-creation.rec>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:671
msgid ""
"A record array representation of a structured array can be obtained using "
"the appropriate :meth:`view <numpy.ndarray.view>`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:674
msgid ""
">>> arr = np.array([(1, 2., 'Hello'), (2, 3., \"World\")],\n"
"...                dtype=[('foo', 'i4'),('bar', 'f4'), ('baz', 'S10')])\n"
">>> recordarr = arr.view(dtype=np.dtype((np.record, arr.dtype)),\n"
"...                      type=np.recarray)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:679
msgid ""
"For convenience, viewing an ndarray as type :class:`numpy.recarray` will "
"automatically convert to :class:`numpy.record` datatype, so the dtype can be "
"left out of the view::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:683
msgid ""
">>> recordarr = arr.view(np.recarray)\n"
">>> recordarr.dtype\n"
"dtype((numpy.record, [('foo', '<i4'), ('bar', '<f4'), ('baz', 'S10')]))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:687
msgid ""
"To get back to a plain ndarray both the dtype and type must be reset. The "
"following view does so, taking into account the unusual case that the "
"recordarr was not a structured type::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:691
msgid ""
">>> arr2 = recordarr.view(recordarr.dtype.fields or recordarr.dtype, np."
"ndarray)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:693
msgid ""
"Record array fields accessed by index or by attribute are returned as a "
"record array if the field has a structured type but as a plain ndarray "
"otherwise. ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:696
msgid ""
">>> recordarr = np.rec.array([('Hello', (1, 2)), (\"World\", (3, 4))],\n"
"...                 dtype=[('foo', 'S6'),('bar', [('A', int), ('B', "
"int)])])\n"
">>> type(recordarr.foo)\n"
"<class 'numpy.ndarray'>\n"
">>> type(recordarr.bar)\n"
"<class 'numpy.rec.recarray'>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.rec.rst:703
msgid ""
"Note that if a field has the same name as an ndarray attribute, the ndarray "
"attribute takes precedence. Such fields will be inaccessible by attribute "
"but will still be accessible by index."
msgstr ""

